{"id":"ox","term":"Ox","source":"Easton's Bible Dictionary (M.G. Easton, 1897)","html":"<p>Heb. bakar, “cattle;” “neat cattle”, (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Genesis 12:16\">Gen. 12:16</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Genesis 34:28\">34:28</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Job 1:3\">Job 1:3</a>, <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Genesis 1:14\">14</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Genesis 42:12\">42:12</a>, etc.); not to be muzzled when treading the corn (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Deuteronomy 25:4\">Deut. 25:4</a>). Referred to by our Lord in his reproof to the Pharisees (<a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Luke 13:15\">Luke 13:15</a>; <a class=\"ref\" data-ref=\"Luke 14:5\">14:5</a>).</p>\n\u0000","refs":["Genesis 12:16","Genesis 34:28","Job 1:3","Genesis 1:14","Genesis 42:12","Deuteronomy 25:4","Luke 13:15","Luke 14:5"]}